# Report Friction Skill

> **Trigger**: Use this skill when a kit template, rule, skill, command, or checklist item did the wrong thing and you want it fixed upstream — or right after a task where the workflow got in your way. READ-ONLY on the project; nothing is sent without an explicit "submit".

## What this skill produces

A clean, non-identifying friction report filed as a GitHub issue against `{{KIT_REPO_SLUG}}`, in the exact five-section feedback taxonomy. It enters the same disposition pipeline as operator-authored feedback: every Suggested-Changes row is answered `SHIPPED` / `DEFERRED` / `REJECTED` / `N-A` in the next release, zero silent drops.

## Procedure

Work through the steps in order. Steps 3 and 5 are gates — do not skip them.

**Step 0 — Context harvest.** Read `.ai-kit-manifest.json` at the project root if present and record `kit_version`, `presets`, `packs`, `maturity_tier`, `ide_scope`. If absent, note "manifest absent — plugin-only install" and use plugin version **0.20.0** as the kit version.

**Step 1 — Defect loop.** Repeat until the user says done. Per defect: repo-RELATIVE **artifact** path + line; **expected vs actual** (BOTH mandatory); **trigger** (prompt / skill / command / phase); **severity** BLOCKER / HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW; optional **suggested change** as `file:line` + proposed text.

**Step 2 — Non-identifying project profile.** BUCKETS ONLY, never names/URLs: stack (frameworks / language / DB); size `<10k` / `10-100k` / `>100k` LOC; team `1` / `2-5` / `6+`; age `<6mo` / `6-24mo` / `>24mo`; presets / tier / surface from Step 0.

**Step 3 — Mechanical sanitization pass (GATE, before rendering).** (1) Replace absolute paths with repo-relative. (2) Replace `{{PROJECT_NAME}}` and the repo directory name with `<project>`. (3) Strip git remotes, internal URLs, emails, `git config` `user.name` / `user.email`, `$USER`. Then RE-SCAN the assembled draft for residual hits and build a **redaction list** of exactly what was redacted.

**Step 4 — Render in the feedback taxonomy.** EXACTLY these five sections, in order: (1) Project Profile; (2) What Worked Well; (3) What Didn't Work — each defect as a `file:line — expected vs actual` row; (4) Missing Patterns; (5) Suggested Changes — `file:line` + proposed-text rows. Defects land in both What Didn't Work and Suggested Changes, keyed by `file:line`.

**Step 5 — User review gate (GATE).** Print the full output plus the redaction list. The user may edit any part. Require an explicit **"submit"** to proceed. On abort, offer to save to `./friction-report-YYYY-MM-DD.md` and send NOTHING.

**Step 6 — Submit.** Preferred: `gh issue create --repo {{KIT_REPO_SLUG}} --title "Friction: <one-line> (kit vX.Y.Z)" --label friction-report --body-file <tmp>`. Fallback (no `gh`): print the body + `https://github.com/{{KIT_REPO_SLUG}}/issues/new?template=friction-report.yml` for manual paste.

**Step 7 — Confirm & close out.** Print the issue URL. Suggest keeping the local copy until the disposition lands in the next `feedback/DISPOSITIONS-vX.Y.Z.md`; the issue is closed with a link to its rows.

## When NOT to Use

- For general impressions without a concrete `file:line` — the report needs actionable rows, not vibes.
- For a project-local convention that will not generalize (that is a DECISIONS.md entry, not upstream friction).
- For anything requiring the project name, a client name, or an absolute path to make sense — if it cannot be sanitized, it cannot be filed.

## Constraints

- READ-ONLY on the project; the only write is the optional local `friction-report-YYYY-MM-DD.md` on abort.
- Steps 3 and 5 are mandatory gates.
- Repo-relative paths only in the body — an absolute path in the output is a defect in this skill.
- Expected AND actual are both required for every defect.
